Suppose we have an object like `f={"t1": "a", "t2": "a"}`. Currently `_.invert(f)` will produce an object `{"a":"t2"}`. While this is a true functional inverse of the object `f` viewed as a function, it is an arbitrarily chosen inverse (`{"a":"t1"}` would be just as good). Wouldn't it be better to view `_.invert` as inverting a (possibly multi valued) ``function'' to produce another possibly multiply valued function? That is, wouldn't it be better to have `_.invert(f)` produce something like ```{ "a": ["t1", "t2"] }``` ?

Moreover, instead of `_.invert({"t1": ["a","b"]})` yielding something not very useful like like `{"a, b": "t1"}` it would give `{"a": "t1", "b": "t1"}`.

I am using the following code instead of `_.invert` to achieve this behavior, although no doubt it is quite poorly written:

```javascript
function inv(a) {
  let pairs = _.flatten(Object.entries(a).map(x=>[].concat(x[1]).map(y=>[y,x[0]])),1);
  let res = {};
  for(let i=0; i < pairs.length; i++) {
    if(!res[pairs[i][0]]) {
      res[pairs[i][0]]=pairs[i][1]
    } else {
      res[pairs[i][0]]=[].concat(res[pairs[i][0]]).concat(pairs[i][1])
    }
  }
  return res
}
```
Feel free to test it out at https://replit.com/@ChrisDock/FirstWretchedSyntax#index.js. As a quick example:

![ex1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4482454/177194472-5c66382c-1a79-45e2-8d9a-691214e288b7.png)


Note that unlike `_.invert`, `inv` actually correctly undoes itself if applied twice. The only asymmetry this approach has is that `inv(inv(obj))` will "unwrap" all singleton lists in obj, but I should note that `_.inv(_.inv(obj))` also does this:

![ex2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4482454/177193689-271da537-95c5-4ca8-9ed8-f095a7200bd6.png)

Also, like `_.invert`, `inv` will cast all non string or array values to string.

