I appreciate all the work done to bring the functional style I'm used to using to lodash with `lodash/fp`, however there seems to be an issue in the implementation that I'm very surprised to find.

The initial value for the accumulator in `lodash/fp/reduce` is created and then seemingly shared across the mapping function below. This results in each reduce function using the same array as an accumulator.  Simply replacing `lodash/fp/reduce` with `_.reduce` and it works as expected.

```typescript
import map from 'lodash/fp/map';
import reduce from 'lodash/fp/reduce';
import flatten from 'lodash/fp/flatten';
import _ from 'lodash';

test('does lodash/fp/reduce work?', () => {
    const stuff = [
        [1, 2],
        [3, 4],
    ];
    const r = map(
        reduce((acc: number[], n: number) => {
            acc.push(n);
            return acc;
        }, [])
    )(stuff);
    const r1 = flatten(r);
    // fails with length 8: [1, 2, 3, 4, 1, 2, 3, 4];
    expect(r1.length).toBe(4);
});

test('does lodash  work?', () => {
    const stuff = [
        [1, 2],
        [3, 4],
    ];
    const r = map((nums: number[]) =>
        _.reduce(
            nums,
            (acc: number[], n: number) => {
                acc.push(n);
                return acc;
            },
            []
        )
    )(stuff);
    const r1 = flatten(r);
    // works great with length 4: [1, 2, 3, 4];
    expect(r1.length).toBe(4);
});
```

